      "source": "### Tree 3\n\n```\n            N\n          /   \\\n         H     R\n        / \\   / \\\n       D   L P   S\n```\n\nThis tree happens to be structured so that its inorder traversal comes out in alphabetical order: `D, H, L, N, P, R, S`. (Go ahead and verify that by tracing it yourself below.)\n\n*This question is a bonus — the concept presented here is beyond the scope of DSA2 and properly covered in DSA3. Give it a try if you're curious, but it won't be expected of you in this course.*\n\n**3j (BONUS).** Tree 1 and Tree 2 do **not** produce alphabetically-ordered inorder traversals, even though their node labels are still just letters. What property does a tree need to have for inorder traversal to always come out in sorted order? You don't need to write code — describe it in your own words.\n\n*Hint: think about how each node's value compares to everything in its left branch versus everything in its right branch — and whether that has to be true just at the root, or at every node in the tree.*\n\nThere's no auto-checker for this one — ask your tutor if you want to check your answer.",
